<DOC><DOCNO> AP890126-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-26-89 1808EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-DestroyerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0647 01-26 0274</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Destroyer Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0274</SECOND><HEAD>Navy Destroyer Runs Aground In Bahamas</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail, including type of naval trainingexercises, length of ship and size of crew, and divers conducting inspection.</HEAD><DATELINE>MAYPORT, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Navy destroyer USS Spruance ran agroundduring anti-submarine warfare exercises near Andros Island in theBahamas, the Navy said Thursday.   No one was injured in the Wednesday night incident, but the563-foot ship had minor damage, said Lt. Cmdr. John Lloyd, aspokesman at Atlantic Fleet surface force headquarters in Norfolk,Va.   Lloyd said the ship, based in Mayport, is in no danger ofsinking. The guided missile frigate USS Boone and Navy tugs wereworking to refloat the Spruance, and divers were conducting aninspection, officials said.   The Navy was investigating the cause of the mishap. Lloyd saidwinds were blowing about 30 mph when the ship ran aground andcontinued strong with gusts up to 35 mph Thursday.   The ship, more than twice the size of World War II destroyers,left Mayport on Tuesday and had been scheduled to return Friday. Thevessel was commissioned on September 1975 and carries a crew of 20officers and 267 enlisted men.   The underwater warfare training takes place in a deep-watertrough east of Andros. The are, where water is as deep as 8,000 feetor more, is fringed by reef-filled shallows.   Andros, the largest of the Bahamian islands, is about 180 mileseast of Key West, Fla. The grounding occurred three miles from of aNavy pier on the island, which is home to the Navy's AtlanticUndersea Test and Evaluation Center.</TEXT></DOC>